  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is that when people from groups historically underrepresented in these fields—like women or people of color—feel the pressure of negative stereotypes about their abilities, it can impair their performance. I’ve seen this in my own life as a carpenter in New York; I’ve had kids who were told they weren’t ‘smart enough’ for science or math, and they shut down. It’s not just about the stereotypes themselves but how they make people anxious and less able to focus. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters. We need to create environments where everyone feels safe to try, not just excel. For me, as a man who’s been depressed and works with my hands, I know that when you’re stressed about being judged, you can’t do your job well. So, addressing stereotype threat means starting with simple things: teachers who don’t assume kids are ‘not good at math,’ or workplaces where people aren’t compared to others. It’s not about fixing the stereotypes but helping people feel like they belong. In my community, volunteering with kids has shown that when they feel seen and supported, they perform better. We need to do this in schools and workplaces, not just in big studies. It’s about making sure everyone has a chance to learn without fear.",
